Are you sure you aren't thinking of, say, "Precious" (with its "fuck off" line) or "Tattooed Love Boys" (with Hynde's quip "I shot my mouth off/And you showed me what that hole was for")?
That the original lyrics of "Tutti Frutti" were not just off-color but full of, as Miller puts it, "thinly veiled anal eroticism"?

As I skim Flowers in the Dustbin for fresh anecdotes (which we agree may be the book's real pleasure), I realize how many of Miller's vignettes seem chosen with an eye to '90s academic interests--gender, thanatos, whiteness studies.
Such apocrypha is the envy of any popular historian, and it's definitely a major selling point for Miller's book.
